                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d99">
                <head>99. <gloss target="#t_Todis_1">Todis</gloss> 35 to Geneva, March 12<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d99fn1">Guidance on handling U.K. declaration on
                        national detection systems. Confidential. 1 p. Department of State, Central
                        Files, 700.5611/3–1262.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1962-03-12T18:17:00-05:00">March 12, 1962, 6:17 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <pb facs="d99-1" n="1" type="facsimile" xml:id="d99-1"/>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_UK_1">UK</gloss> idea of declaring that we will rely on
                    national detection systems when scientific developments permit would open door
                    to proposals for atmospheric test ban to be monitored by national systems. Since
                    our position is that Soviet rejection of treaty along lines of April 18 draft
                    constitutes rejection of President’s March 2 offer, we believe that <pb
                        facs="0436" n="285" type="typeset" xml:id="pg_285"/> initial emphasis must
                    be placed on control system envisaged in that treaty. We would therefore not
                    favor adding proposed <gloss target="#t_UK_1">UK</gloss> declaration.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed corresp="#p_BGW_1">
                        <persName corresp="#p_BGW_1">Ball</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
